Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[_Austropotamobius pallipes_, the white-clawed crayfish of Western European streams, has become restricted in distribution over the past century.

Crayfish fungal plague, fatal to white-clawed crayfish, has affected many European countries. It is caused by a fungus _Aphanomyces astaci_ that was brought into Europe by the introduction of _Procambarus clarkii_, a freshwater crayfish species of Lousiana, USA, which is naturally infected by this pathogen, although it does not develop clinical disease.

For a picture of a white-clawed crayfish go to http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austropotamobius_pallipes#mediaviewer/File:Austropotamobius_pallipes.jpg. - Mod.PMB


A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5142833,39.]
